T1  - Stock Rationing
AU  - Kaplan, Alan
Y1  - 1969/01/01
PY  - 1969
DA  - 1969/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.15.5.260
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.15.5.260
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 260
EP  - 267
VL  - 15
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A supplier may distinguish between the demands be receives for an item, attaching greater importance to satisfying some categories of demand than others. This paper discusses use of reserve levels, i. e, stock levels at which to stop issuing in response to lower priority demand. An algorithm which calculates optimum reserve levels is developed. Its effectiveness is compared to use of unsophisticated policies.
AB  - A supplier may distinguish between the demands be receives for an item, attaching greater importance to satisfying some categories of demand than others. This paper discusses use of reserve levels, i. e, stock levels at which to stop issuing in response to lower priority demand. An algorithm which calculates optimum reserve levels is developed. Its effectiveness is compared to use of unsophisticated policies.
